  "unmapped_findings": [
    "The stacking fault energy (SFE) values of austenite: 0.5C steel 73.4 mJ/m^2, 0.8C steel 77.9 mJ/m^2, 1.2C steel 84.5 mJ/m^2, according to previous model [13].",
    "The 0.8C steel exhibits the highest tensile strength of 979 MPa, and its specific strength is 142.3 MPa·cm^3/g.",
    "The product of ultimate tensile strength and total elongation (UTS × TE): 0.5C 28100 MPa·%, 0.8C 37597 MPa·%, 1.2C 53205 MPa·%.",
    "The 0.8C steel's mechanical properties are comparable to the Fe-27Mn-12Al-0.8C steel (995 MPa, 42%) reported in Ref. [10].",
    "The 1.2C steel exhibits a superior combination of strength and ductility (UTS 946.7 MPa, elongation 56.2%), with UTS × TE of 53205 MPa·%.",
    "The strain hardening rate curves (Fig. 4) show: 0.5C and 0.8C steels have a continuously decreasing trend, while 1.2C steel sustains a sufficient strain hardening rate beyond 0.026 strain.",
    "The C-J analysis reveals that the strain hardening behavior is linked to the evolution of dislocation structures: planar slip, Taylor lattice, microbands, and microband interactions.",
    "In 0.5C steel during tensile deformation: at ε=0.02, planar slip in austenite and dislocation tangles in ferrite; at ε=0.18, Taylor lattice and microbands in austenite, dense dislocation tangles in ferrite.",
    "In 0.8C steel: at ε=0.01, planar slip in austenite and paired superdislocations in ferrite; at ε=0.18, microbands in austenite and increased dislocation density in ferrite.",
    "In 1.2C steel: at ε=0.02, planar slip; at ε=0.07, Taylor lattice; at ε=0.3, well-developed microbands; at ε=0.4, interaction between microbands."
